John Edward: linguistic skills are vital for citizens of the world
The independent schools in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding results in the exams, which is further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these independent schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS, for short), are striving to deliver the best possible service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare their pupils for further education, for the career they choose and for the place they will occupy in the world.
As a modern language, it is observed that modern languages are still popular and in demand in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, that goes to his head. If you talk to him in his own language, that goes to his heart."
If you talk to him in his language, it reaches his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you can &apos; t rely solely on English.
If we look at the recent results of the examinations, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking tables, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
Overall, 68 per cent of the students who studied foreign languages received an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that make up the SCIS, showed that 72 % of students achieved an A in Mandarin, while 72 % of those studying German, 69 % of those studying French and 63 % of those studying Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a fundamental skill that children and young people will need in the future without a doubt.
Languages are now considered on a par with the CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere else.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 revealed that 17 per cent of employers cited language skills as a barrier to filling jobs.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly indispensable for preparing young people for their future careers.
The potential for language skills in the workplace is increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Whether someone chooses to pursue a career or learn a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to this competition, which will last a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give that person an edge over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 per cent of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and it was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15 per cent, was French.
For this reason, learning languages is now important for today &apos; s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, they will be better equipped to find a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the more important languages for the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child &apos; s interests, independent schools will always offer a choice of several languages taught by specialist staff.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
In a global business environment, languages remain vital to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages are "competencies for international communication."
Independent schools in Scotland will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people.
Fair enough.
