Harvard students take a course on how to sleep enough.
Thanks to a new course being offered this year at Harvard University, all university students are now sleeping more in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture of all-night caffeine-fuelled cramming.
A professor at the world &apos; s number one university discovered that students there often had no idea about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
His motivation to start the course came after giving a talk on how sleep deprivation affects learning.
At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked why she was just hearing about this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever told him the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a psychiatry professor at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university &apos; s health services, noted that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were sleeping only during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, athletic shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of establishing a routine for going to bed.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
After that, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
We know that changing student behaviour will not happen overnight.
We believe that they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” added Professor Czeisler.
He said that the culture of "all-nighters" still existed and added that modern technology and increased pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and a good night's sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation makes the brain feel hungry, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the whole campus.
He hopes the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar programme of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler &apos; s recommendation is that students set an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of blue light emitted by computer screens and LED lights, which can disrupt circadian rhythms, so they will have trouble falling asleep.
