The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
The experts will analyse the sounds picked up in the recordings to determine the frequency of the calls of the bats and the species that make them.
A report and map of the habitat will then be produced to provide a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of grasslands and how to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development that affects their nests and loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical cabling can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticides and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Mosquitoes are not actually blind.
