The organization has even opened the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of bat in Scotland.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
Here at Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, many veteran trees and the right habitat.
However, there is still much to be learned about bats, and the work we do here and at other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before maintenance work is carried out, as a colony of bats can be accidentally destroyed and 400 females and young can be killed, which would wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
